        <h2>What LLM Visibility Means</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>LLM visibility is whether your brand, product, or domain appears — accurately and credibly — within the text generated by a large language model when a user asks a relevant question.</strong>
          It is distinct from search ranking, click-through rate, or impression share. A brand with excellent LLM visibility is mentioned, described, and sometimes cited with a source link inside AI-generated answers. A brand with poor LLM visibility is absent from those answers, even when it would be the most relevant recommendation.
        </p>

        <p>
          The distinction matters because the user behaviour driving AI search is fundamentally different from traditional search. A user who receives an AI-generated answer is far less likely to scroll through additional sources — they act on what the model tells them. If your brand is not in that answer, you do not exist for that user in that moment. LLM visibility optimisation is the discipline of ensuring you are in the answer.
        </p>

        <p>
          This page focuses on the concept and core tactics of LLM visibility. It is one part of the broader <a href="/ai-brand-visibility/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">AI brand visibility</a> strategy, which addresses how brands are perceived and cited across all AI-powered surfaces. The wider context for all of this work sits within <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">generative engine optimisation</a> (GEO) as a discipline.
        </p>

        <h3>Visibility vs. Ranking</h3>
        <p>
          Traditional SEO optimises for position in a ranked list. LLM visibility optimises for inclusion in generated prose. These require overlapping but distinct skill sets. A page ranked first in Google may be completely absent from a ChatGPT response to the same query — and vice versa. Brands that conflate the two optimisation objectives tend to under-invest in the signals that actually drive AI citation: entity authority, content self-containedness, and structural clarity.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2 -->
      <section id="how-llms-surface-brands" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>How LLMs Surface Brands in Responses</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Two distinct mechanisms determine whether a brand appears in an LLM response: parametric knowledge encoded during model training, and retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) that fetches live documents at query time.</strong>
          Most deployed AI systems — including ChatGPT with Browse, Perplexity, and Google AI Overviews — use a hybrid of both. Understanding the mechanics of each is essential for targeting the right tactics.
        </p>

        <h3>Parametric Knowledge</h3>
        <p>
          When a model is trained, it compresses patterns from its training corpus into model weights. Brands that are mentioned frequently, consistently, and authoritatively in that corpus develop a strong parametric presence — the model "knows" them without needing to retrieve additional information. Building parametric visibility requires sustained investment in third-party coverage: press, industry publications, analyst reports, Wikipedia entries, and Wikidata records. This is a long-horizon strategy; its effects compound over successive model versions but cannot be directly accelerated within a single training cycle.
        </p>

        <h3>Retrieval-Augmented Generation</h3>
        <p>
          RAG-enabled platforms fetch candidate documents before generating a response. Your content can only influence RAG-based responses if it is: indexed and accessible to the platform's crawler; selected by the retrieval system as a high-confidence source for the query; and structured in a way that the model can extract a clean, citable answer from. RAG visibility is more directly actionable than parametric visibility — improvements to crawlability, content structure, and schema markup can yield measurable citation gains within weeks.
        </p>

        <p>
          For platform-specific RAG optimisation tactics covering ChatGPT, Perplexity, and Gemini, see our guide to <a href="/optimise-for-ai-platforms/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">optimising for specific AI platforms</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 3 -->
