        <h2>The Five Core LLM Visibility Signals</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>LLM visibility is the product of five compounding signals — each addressable independently, but most effective when developed together.</strong>
          Weakness in any single signal creates a ceiling on overall visibility, regardless of how strong the others are.
        </p>

        <div class="not-prose mt-8 space-y-5">

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">1. Entity Authority</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Entity authority is the degree to which your brand is a well-defined, unambiguous entity in the knowledge graph. It is built through Wikidata records, Wikipedia articles, consistent NAP (name/address/phone) data, sameAs schema properties, and authoritative third-party mentions that all use the same brand name and attributes. High entity authority means models can identify and describe your brand accurately, without confusion with similarly named entities.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">2. Content Citability</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Content citability is the structural property that makes a passage extractable and usable by an AI system. It requires self-contained sentences that are interpretable without context, declarative factual statements rather than hedged commentary, clear attribution to a named source, and a format — definitions, numbered lists, comparison tables — that maps onto how AI systems construct responses. Content with high citability is selected more often by retrieval systems and quoted more accurately in generated answers.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">3. Topical Authority Depth</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Topical authority depth is measured by the breadth and depth of coverage across a subject cluster. A site that covers a topic comprehensively — with pages that address core concepts, sub-topics, adjacent questions, and specific use cases — signals domain expertise to both traditional search and AI retrieval systems. The GEOoptimised topical map approach (ROOT → NODE → SEED) is designed to build this signal systematically, ensuring every retrieval query in a topic cluster finds a relevant, authoritative page on this site.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">4. Structured Data Signals</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              JSON-LD schema markup — particularly Organisation, Article, FAQPage, and BreadcrumbList — provides AI retrieval systems with pre-parsed metadata about your content. This reduces the ambiguity cost of retrieving and citing your pages. A page with valid schema is interpreted with higher confidence than a page of equivalent prose quality with no structured data. For the full implementation guide, see our page on <a href="/schema-markup-ai/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">schema markup for AI</a>.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">5. Crawler Accessibility</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Content that AI crawlers cannot access cannot appear in RAG-based responses. Crawler accessibility requires an accurate robots.txt that permits AI crawlers (GPTBot, PerplexityBot, ClaudeBot, Googlebot), a correctly formed sitemap, fast page load times, and no JavaScript rendering dependencies that prevent crawlers from reading page content. An llms.txt file provides an additional signal to AI crawlers about the site's purpose and the most important content to index.
            </p>
          </div>

        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 4 -->
      <section id="citation-ready-content" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Writing Citation-Ready Content</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Citation-ready content is not a style preference — it is a structural property that determines whether an AI system can extract and use a passage when generating a response.</strong>
          Research into LLM citation behaviour consistently shows that content format is as important as content quality: a well-researched page written in discursive narrative is cited less often than a comparable page structured around clear definitions, enumerated points, and explicit factual statements.
        </p>

        <p>
          The structural elements that most reliably produce citation-ready content are:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Lead with the definition.</strong> Begin every section with a bold declarative statement that defines or summarises the core concept. This sentence should be interpretable as a standalone quote.</li>
          <li><strong>Use explicit attribution.</strong> Attribute claims to named sources, studies, or organisations. "According to..." constructions increase the probability that an AI system will cite the source rather than paraphrase without attribution.</li>
          <li><strong>Prefer specific over hedged language.</strong> "Brand visibility improves by 40% when entity records are complete" is more citable than "brand visibility can sometimes improve when entities are well-defined."</li>
          <li><strong>Structure for extraction.</strong> Use H2/H3 headings that mirror likely query phrasing, comparison tables, and numbered lists. These formats map directly onto how AI systems construct responses to how/what/which queries.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep answers self-contained.</strong> Every FAQ answer, section summary, or callout box should be interpretable without reading the rest of the page. AI extraction does not preserve surrounding context.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          For the specific mechanics of how content survives the chunking and retrieval process, see our companion page on <a href="/llm-context-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">LLM context optimisation</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

